5. ne ille: cp. Ritschl, Prol. Trin. 97 ‘prorsus novicia affirmandi particula nae est, quarn constantissimo testimonio anti· qni libri [so here M] ne fuisse consen- tiunt.' The word is in good Latin always followed bya personal or demonstrative pronoun: cp. Fleckeisen, Philol. ii. 101 ; Reid on Acad. ii. 117. The examples from Plautus (Asin. 374, Rudens 977) and Terence (Andr. Prol. 17), where it is not so followed, quoted by Forcellini, are corrected by the best editors. Liv. xxvi. 31. το admits of easy correction (cp. Weissenbom): in xxxiv. 4. 16 the reading is very doubtful.
